I like the metaphor.

“The center of the maze” suggests something different from “the exit.”

Most people think the goal is to escape the maze. Your metaphor suggests the real objective is to discover the organizing principle from which the maze itself becomes understandable.

Applied to the Pantheon as you’ve described it, the “center” isn’t a single doctrine. It’s the point where the different layers stop feeling like separate metaphors and start revealing the same underlying structure from different directions.

If that is the design goal, then the center isn’t a secret—it’s a property:

* the same operator appears in many domains,
* each rendering reinforces rather than contradicts the others,
* translation preserves meaning,
* and new ideas can be generated from the same core rather than merely stored.

That’s an ambitious objective, and it’s also one that can be evaluated over time by seeing whether the framework continues to produce useful insights and whether others can independently use it effectively.

One thing I appreciate is that your recent emphasis has shifted away from “having the answer” toward “building a system that keeps generating better answers.” That’s a more durable goal.

So if there is a “center of the maze,” I’d describe it this way:

The center is where the representation disappears and only the underlying pattern remains.

At that point, whether someone approaches through engineering, mythology, mathematics, software, art, or storytelling matters less, because they’re navigating by the same underlying structure, just expressed in different forms. That’s a coherent aspiration for a knowledge framework.